# Indian Dairy Market Structure

The Indian dairy industry is divided into the organized and unorganized segments. The unorganized segment consists of traditional milkmen, vendors and self-consumption at home and the organized segment consists of cooperatives and private dairies as illustrated in the flowchart below:

<!-- Flowchart -->
Indian Dairy Market
├── Organised Dairy Market
│   ├── Cooperatives
│   └── Private Dairies
└── Unorganised Dairy Market
    ├── Traditional Milkmen / Vendors
    └── Self Consumption at Home

(Source: IMARC Report)

In 2014, 30% of the total marketable milk in India was processed by the organized segment, with private players processing 55% and cooperatives processing 45% of the total marketable milk in the organized segment as illustrated in the chart below:

<!-- Charts -->
**Milk production volume break-up by Marketability**
- Self Consumption: 54%
- Marketable Milk: 46%

**Marketable Milk volume break-up by Segment**
- Organised: 70%
- Unorganised: 30%

**Organized Marketable Milk volume break-up by Segment**
- Private Players: 55%
- Cooperatives & Government: 45%

(Source: IMARC Report)

During 2010 to 2014, the organized segment grew at a CAGR 20.7% whilst the unorganized segment grew at a CAGR of 14.2% during the same period. However, the unorganized segment still dominates the Indian dairy industry at 80% compared to the organized segment at 20% by value in 2014. The organized segment is expected to grow at a CAGR of 19.5% between 2015 to 2020, accounting for approximately 25.5% of the Indian dairy industry by 2020. The unorganized segment is expected to grow at a CAGR of 13.2% during the same period and is expected to account for 74.5% of the total Indian dairy industry by 2020.

(Source: IMARC Report)

